<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Get Wrong</h2>

  <h3>Making Pots Too Early</h3>
  <p>
    They can break down before planting.
  </p>

  <h3>Using Too Thin Paper</h3>
  <p>
    Leads to weak, unstable pots.
  </p>

  <h3>Overwatering</h3>
  <p>
    Accelerates breakdown.
  </p>

  <h3>Trying to Scale Up Too Much</h3>
  <p>
    Slows down the process significantly.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When Paper Pot Makers Make the Most Sense</h2>

  <p>
    They work best when:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>you’re starting a manageable number of plants</li>
    <li>you want to avoid transplant shock</li>
    <li>you prefer reusable or low-waste systems</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Outside of those situations, simpler systems may be more efficient.
  </p>
</section>

